      "source": "Method\n\nWe used tabular Q-learning in the stochastic windy gridworld, and compared two exploration policies:\n\n\\(\\epsilon\\)-greedy  \nSoftmax (Boltzmann) with temperature \\(\\tau\\)\n\nThe Q-update used in both cases is:\n\n\

\[\nQ(s_t,a_t) \\leftarrow Q(s_t,a_t) + \\alpha \\Big[ r_{t+1} + \\gamma \\max_{a'} Q(s_{t+1},a') - Q(s_t,a_t) \\Big]\n\\]

\n\nwith terminal handling:\n\n\

\[\n\\max_{a'} Q(s_{t+1},a') = 0 \\quad \\text{if } done = \\text{True}.\n\\]

\n\nExploration policies:\n\n\

\[\n\\pi_{\\epsilon}(a \\mid s) =\n\\begin{cases}\n1 - \\epsilon + \\dfrac{\\epsilon}{|A|}, & a = \\arg\\max_b Q(s,b) \\\\\\n\\dfrac{\\epsilon}{|A|}, & \\text{otherwise}\n\\end{cases}\n\\]

\n\n\

\[\n\\pi_{\\tau}(a \\mid s) = \\dfrac{\\exp\\!\\big(Q(s,a)/\\tau\\big)}{\\sum_b \\exp\\!\\big(Q(s,b)/\\tau\\big)}\n\\]

\n\nAlgorithm (Q-learning with selectable exploration)\n\nInitialize \\(Q(s,a)=0\\) for all \\((s,a)\\)\n\nFor each timestep:\n\nchoose action \\(a_t\\) from either \\(\\epsilon\\)-greedy or softmax policy\n\nexecute \\(a_t\\), observe \\((r_{t+1}, s_{t+1}, done)\\)\n\nupdate \\(Q(s_t,a_t)\\) with the equation above\n\nif terminal: reset environment\n\nComparison Figure\n\nInclude one plot with average return vs timesteps (averaged over repetitions), containing:\n\n\\(\\epsilon\\)-greedy curves for several \\(\\epsilon\\) values (e.g., 0.01, 0.1, 0.3)\n\nsoftmax curves for several \\(\\tau\\) values (e.g., 0.01, 0.1, 1.0)\n\nCaption example:\n\n“Comparison of exploration strategies in stochastic windy gridworld. Curves are averaged over \\(N\\) repetitions and smoothed with window \\(w\\).”\n\nInterpretation\n\nSmall \\(\\epsilon\\) or small \\(\\tau\\): faster exploitation, but risk of insufficient exploration.\n\nLarge \\(\\epsilon\\) or large \\(\\tau\\): more exploration, but slower convergence.\n\nIn our runs, the best performance was obtained at moderate exploration (replace with your best setting: \\(\\epsilon=\\dots\\) or \\(\\tau=\\dots\\)).\n\nPreferred method:\n\nI prefer softmax when I want smoother, value-sensitive exploration (actions with higher \\(Q\\) are sampled more often, not just greedy vs random).\n\nI prefer \\(\\epsilon\\)-greedy when simplicity and speed are more important.\n\nRL vs Dynamic Programming optimum\n\nRL may approach DP performance, but often does not exactly match it in finite training because:\n\nfinite samples (not full model access),\n\nstochastic transitions/wind,\n\nexploration noise during learning,\n\nhyperparameter sensitivity \\((\\alpha,\\epsilon,\\tau)\\),\n\npossible non-convergence in limited time.\n\nSo DP is typically the reference upper bound (with full model), while model-free RL is a sample-based approximation that can get close but may remain below it."
